@node EDITOR "The screen setup of the editor"

  The screen for the editor is divided into two sections: The large area
  above is the editing zone. Your mouse changes into a animated cursor
  which indicates your current position. Click left to place the first
  editing block, or click right to place second editing block. Move the
  mouse to the edges of the edit area to scroll through large levels

  The small panel below is the @{"menu section" link MENU}. (<-- select for details!)

  Apart of the menu there are some keyboard instructions to use:

    C ............. clear level in edit area
    T ............. test level in edit area
    X ............. use next block for first editing block (red)
    <Shift> + X ... use next block for second editing block (blue)
    Y ............. use previous block for first editing block (red)
    <Shift> + Y ... use previous block for second editing block (blue)
    <Del> ......... erase current or all levels in memory
    Cursor Keys ... scrolls level into desired direction
    F1 - F10 ...... shortcut to get levels 1,6,...,41,46

  Of course there appear alert boxes (see menu section) and a file
  selector. The @{"file selector" link FSEL} first tries the volume "DCLevels:".
  Otherwise it uses the local sub-directory "Levels". That's all.

@endnode
@node MENU "What to do on the menu panel"

  On the righthand-side are the editing tiles. Click with the left mouse
  on them to change first editing block (red flash) or click with right
  mouse button to change second editing block (blue flashing). And on the
  lefthand-side are the following menu options:

    @{BD "QUIT"}

  Quits back to workbench. You must confirm if you really want to quit.

    @{BD "INFO"}

  Displays an information box with the name of the loaded level set in
  memory, the name of the creator and the free memory. You can use up
  to 24 characters for your name. Click any mouse button to remove the
  information box.

    @{BD "Setting"}

  Here you define all required data for the current level. Click on the
  arrow buttons to change the values up or down.
   - level name (max. 24 characters)
   - level comment or informations (max. 48 characters)
   - available time (left changes minutes, right changes seconds)
   - x-size (in steps of 2 fields, min: 20, max:60)
   - y-size (in steps of 2 fields, min: 16, max:52)
   - diamonds to collect (left change by 1, right change by 10 pieces)
   - start position (use SET button to set the position directly)
   - exit position (use SET button to set the position directly)
   - sub menus for @{"transporters" link TRANS}, @{"baddy homes" link BADDY} and @{"warp fields" link WARPS}
  Click OKAY to use this settings (with sub menus) or CANCEL to abort.

    @{BD "Load"}

  Opens a @{"file selector" link FSEL} to load a new level set into memory. After
  decoding the first level will be displayed. If your selected levels
  doesn't exist or can't be loaded you will be informed with an error
  message.

    @{BD "Save"}

  Opens a @{"file selector" link FSEL} to save your levels from memory. If your file
  already exists you will be asked to overwrite it. If the filename
  doesn't end with ".LEV" it will be added automatically. If saving
  was successful you'll get a message, else you will be informed what
  has gone wrong. Contact @{"me" link INFOS} if you get an "DISC ERROR - CODE:##" error
  with the number ##. (Important!)

    @{BD "Get"}

  Here you store the level from the edit area with the current setting
  into memory with the selected level number. The level will be tested
  for transporter settings, amount of diamonds and some other things.

    @{BD "Put"}

  Here you get the selected level number from memory into the edit area
  with the settings.

    @{BD "(xx,yy)"}

  Here you simply see the current cursor position. It may be useful if
  you want to start designing in the centre or to place baddy homes.

    @{BD "< LV >"}

  Here you set the level number for PUT and GET. The "<" decreases level
  number LV, and ">" increases level number LV. At the levels 1 and 50
  the number warpes around.

@endnode
