@node INSTALL "Install to HD or Floppy"


  Requirements:
  ~~~~~~~~~~~~~
   -> any Amiga
   -> memory: 380K chip, 320K fast to run, 188K disc space to install
   -> and Workbench 1.3 (or above) to run that thing... I'm not sure if
      the game runs with workbench 1.2 or lower. So please upgrade!


  Install to Hard disc:
  ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
     Only copy all files into your "DiamChall" drawer. The editor looks
     for the "Levels" directory to load/save your created level files.


  Install to Floppy disc:
  ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
     Not recommented. But if there is enough disc space on the disc
     copy all files into the same directory of the game. That's it.

       or

     You copy the editor on a formated and bootable disc and create
     a drawer named "Levels". Then you have enough free space to
     create lots of levels.

       or

     Read the game manual @{"instructions" link DC_ManualV1_3.Guide/INSTALL}.

@endnode
@node HINTS "How to test a level-set"

  For me it's very easy, because I have a separate game programm and can
  define which level to play to testing it. For you and all others I have
  two suggestions:

   a) Start with the last level, number 50. Then continue with level 49,
      and so on until you reach the first level. Creating the levels in
      reversed other is hard, so you may use the other way.

   b) Use one warp at level 1 near the start. Set the destination level
      to the next level you want to test, and use <ALWAYS FROM START> to
      enter the warp immediately.

  Limitations for some field types:

   picks: 400, bombs: 200, maps: 20, diamonds: 800, empty fields: 90%


  I guess all of you want to know: "Are there cheats for testing?"
  Short answer from me: "YES, there are cheats." But it would be very
  easy just to type them here.
  I've encoded the @{"cheat text" link CHEATS} with ROT13 for all characters with ASCII
  code between 33 and 126. Sorry, but programmers are prefered to decode
  the text. You can also configure GoldED or other text editors to do it.

@endnode
